# Bioluminescent Enhancements Walkthrough

Here are the changes deployed to the bioluminescent effect:

## 1. Odd-Shaped, Rotated Rectangles
Instead of drawing square points, every point now has a unique shape and orientation!
- [render.vert](file:///Users/2b/Library/CloudStorage/GoogleDrive-brian.rio11@gmail.com/My%20Drive/%F0%9F%94%B5/01%20Grad%20School/02%20SP26/03%20It%27s%20Shader%20Time/W8%20-%20GPU%20Computing/src/shaders/render.vert) scales the particles up to a maximum size of 60.0 pixels so they have enough mathematical resolution.
- [render.frag](file:///Users/2b/Library/CloudStorage/GoogleDrive-brian.rio11@gmail.com/My%20Drive/%F0%9F%94%B5/01%20Grad%20School/02%20SP26/03%20It%27s%20Shader%20Time/W8%20-%20GPU%20Computing/src/shaders/render.frag) utilizes a 2D Rotation Matrix (`mat2 rotate2d`) to twist the local pixel coordinate space (`gl_PointCoord`). 
- It then calculates a random width (e.g., `0.2 - 1.0` scale) and height (e.g., `0.1 - 0.4` scale) for that specific particle and throws away any pixels that fall outside the bounds using `discard;`.
- The net result is thousands of lightweight rotated rectangles flying around!

## 2. Reduced Density
- Lowered the offscreen simulation FBO size from `512x512` down to `64x64`. 
- This reduces the total particle count from 262,144 down to 4,096.
- The scene now has significantly more empty space ("negative space") between the glowing elements, making the individual shapes much easier to distinguish.

## 3. Full-Screen Flash
- Updated the main Javascript [tick()](file:///Users/2b/Library/CloudStorage/GoogleDrive-brian.rio11@gmail.com/My%20Drive/%F0%9F%94%B5/01%20Grad%20School/02%20SP26/03%20It%27s%20Shader%20Time/W8%20-%20GPU%20Computing/src/index.js#123-150) function in [index.js](file:///Users/2b/Library/CloudStorage/GoogleDrive-brian.rio11@gmail.com/My%20Drive/%F0%9F%94%B5/01%20Grad%20School/02%20SP26/03%20It%27s%20Shader%20Time/W8%20-%20GPU%20Computing/src/index.js).
- It now mathematically polls the `timeSinceClick` delta directly on the CPU.
- When `timeSinceClick` is less than 0.2 seconds, it lerps `scene.background` away from Pitch Black to Pure White, creating an incredibly bright, instantaneous "flash" that blows out the screen before receding into the bioluminescent particle animations.

## How to Test
1. Make sure your local browser tab at `http://localhost:8000` is open.
2. Refresh the page so the browser downloads the latest [.frag](file:///Users/2b/Library/CloudStorage/GoogleDrive-brian.rio11@gmail.com/My%20Drive/%F0%9F%94%B5/01%20Grad%20School/02%20SP26/03%20It%27s%20Shader%20Time/W3%20-%20Shader%20Pipeline/map.frag) and [.vert](file:///Users/2b/Library/CloudStorage/GoogleDrive-brian.rio11@gmail.com/My%20Drive/%F0%9F%94%B5/01%20Grad%20School/02%20SP26/03%20It%27s%20Shader%20Time/W3%20-%20Shader%20Pipeline/map.vert) changes.
3. Click your mouse! You'll see the heavy white flash and the much larger, oddly-shaped rotated rectangular particles!
